06970nam a22009615i 9780674292819DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742928197 a10.4159/97806742928192doi  a(DE-B1597)642342  a(OCoLC)1366102316  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aPHI0190002bisacsh1 aKolodny, Niko, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Pecking Order :bSocial Hierarchy as a Philosophical Problem /cNiko Kolodny. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (432 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: A Negative Observation and a Positive Conjecture -- tI A First Instance of the Negative Observation: Justifying the State -- t1 The Received Materials: Improvement and Invasion -- t2 Is the Claim against the State’s Force? -- t3 Is the Claim against the State’s Threats? -- t4 Last Attempts -- tII The Positive Conjecture: Claims against Inferiority -- t5 Relations of Inferiority -- t6 Disparities of Regard -- t7 Reductive Gambits -- t8 The State and the Secondary Tempering Factors -- t9 The State and the Firm -- t10 Collective Inferiority -- tIII Further Instances -- t11 Claims against Corruption: The Negative Observation -- t12 Claims against Corruption: The Positive Conjecture -- t13 Claims against Discrimination -- t14 Claims to Equal Treatment -- t15 Claims to the Rule of Law -- t16 Claims to Equal Liberty -- t17 Claims to Equality of Opportunity -- t18 Claims against Poverty, Relative and Absolute -- t19 Claims against Illiberal Interventions: The Negative Observation -- t20 Claims against Illiberal Interventions: The Positive Conjecture -- tIV Contrasts -- t21 Being No Worse Off -- t22 Relations of Equality -- t23 Nondomination -- tV A Last Instance: Democracy -- t24 Preliminaries -- t25 The Negative Observation: Correspondence -- t26 The Negative Observation: Influence -- t27 The Positive Conjecture: Equal Influence -- tVI A Democracy Too Lenient and Too Demanding? -- t28 Pathologies of American Democracy -- t29 The Permissiveness of Formal Equality -- t30 Gerrymandering: A Case Study of Permissiveness -- t31 The Demandingness of Informal Equality -- t32 Arbitrary Voting -- tConclusion: Not So Much Liberty As Noninferiority -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA trenchant case for a novel philosophical position: that our political thinking is driven less by commitments to freedom or fairness than by an aversion to hierarchy.Niko Kolodny argues that, to a far greater extent than we recognize, our political thinking is driven by a concern to avoid relations of inferiority. In order to make sense of the most familiar ideas in our political thought and discourse—the justification of the state, democracy, and rule of law, as well as objections to paternalism and corruption—we cannot merely appeal to freedom, as libertarians do, or to distributive fairness, as liberals do. We must instead appeal directly to claims against inferiority—to the conviction that no one should stand above or below.The problem of justifying the state, for example, is often billed as the problem of reconciling the state with the freedom of the individual. Yet, Kolodny argues, once we press hard enough on worries about the state’s encroachment on the individual, we end up in opposition not to unfreedom but to social hierarchy. To make his case, Kolodny takes inspiration from two recent trends in philosophical thought: on the one hand, the revival of the republican and Kantian traditions, with their focus on domination and dependence; on the other, relational egalitarianism, with its focus on the effects of the distribution of income and wealth on our social relations.The Pecking Order offers a detailed account of relations of inferiority in terms of objectionable asymmetries of power, authority, and regard. Breaking new ground, Kolodny looks ahead to specific kinds of democratic institutions that could safeguard against such relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aautonomy.  achoice.  acitizenship.  acoercion.  aconsideration.  acontrol.  adiscrimination.  aelections.  aequal treatment.  aesteem.  aforce.  agerrymandering.  ainequality.  ainfluence.  ajohn rawls.  ajustice.  alegitimacy.  aliberty.  amajority rule.  aopportunity.  arights.  avoting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2023 Englishz978311131922308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2023z9783111318646oZDB-23-DPH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z97831107497000 cprintz978067424815140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674292819?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674292819423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674292819/original  a978-3-11-074970-0  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131922-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2023  aZ